<methods><methodStep><description><section>
<title>Field collection.</title>
<para>During each visit physical variables are measured and water samples are collected. 
Temperature and oxygen concentration are measured 0.5 meters below the water?s surface 
using a YSI field oxygen probe. Light is measured using a Licor spherical quantum sensor, in 
the air and 0.5, 1.0, and 2.0 meters below the water?s surface. Secchi depth is also measured. 
Current flow is also measured using a wooden current cross. Water samples are collected from 
0.5 meters below the water?s surface using a peristaltic pump. Zooplankton samples are also 
collected; one set (microzooplankton, in triplicate, used to enumerate rotifers, nauplii, veligers 
and tintinnid ciliates) using the peristaltic pump and a 35 micron mesh plankton net, and a 
second set (macrozooplankton, in triplicate, used to enumerate copepods and cladocerans) using 
a calibrated open-diaphragm bilge pump and a 73 micron mesh plankton net. The concentrated 
zooplankton samples are treated with carbonated water (used as a narcotizing agent) and then 
preserved in a buffered 4&#37; formaldehyde solution (60 grams of sucrose per liter and 8.4 grams 
of sodium bicarbonate per liter) to yield a final formaldehyde concentration of 2&#37;. A 19 
milliliter whole water sample is preserved in 1 milliliter of 20&#37; buffered formaldehyde (30 
grams of sodium borate per liter) for enumeration of bacterial abundance using the acridine 
orange direct count method. A field-filtered, sulfuric acid preserved, sample (in triplicate) is 
also collected for DOC analysis.

For lab analyses and references for more detailed method information, refer to http://www.carydata.org/hudsonriver/HRKingston&#37;20metadata.pdf. </para>
</section></description></methodStep>
